metadata.name: Circumscript #13
metadata.description:
It has always been a goal of mine to incorporate the worlds of physical and digital art together in a piece. And with circumscript I am the closest I've ever been. Circumscript uses a custom shader written to mix and "dilute" the colors on the canvas, thus creating a very physical feeling piece.

This dilution can be more or less depending on the edition, but always plays a huge role in the feel of the piece.


Happy new year.


----


[m] or [double tap] : opens the export/settings menu, use this menu to change the resolution, and make sure to press the reload button if you do.
[holding down] : zooms in on a certain area of the piece, depending on where your mouse/finger is. Use this feature to expore the complex textures of the piece in more detail, it's highly recommended to do this on a higher resolution setting.

The outputs can vary slighty per device, as there's a slight difference in how certain math gets interpreted on different devices with shaders.


----


Made with p5.js and webgl by Wouter Missler in 2022/3.

metadata.name: Isola della Scala #57
metadata.description:
All things pass, all things flow,
Movement, connection, separation, all in tow.
A misstep and we're knocked off course,
But in the end, we rise, as if by force.
Like a dance of dominoes, we fall and we stand,
In this ever-changing world, we're a part of the grand.

The name of this work is the name of the city where my roots began, where the path of everything changed and new directions in life were taken.

Made with p5.js, p5.grain and much love

metadata.name: Digital Gardens #246
metadata.description:
Digital Gardens are places of magic and wonder, where you can connect with your inner nature and take a deep breath. Digital Gardens are a refuge from the world outside. A sanctuary for the mind, body, and soul. But they are also a place of play and exploration. It is a space where you can let your imagination run wild, creating and discovering new things.
Digital Gardens brings to life the minimalistic essence of Detegus’ art and the abstract and rational art of Alfredo Boaron.
The gardens are generated from a recursive function dividing the space at each iteration with a proportion that follows the Fibonacci succession and randomly stops after some iterations. At each recursion the canvas is divided into two pieces following the proportion of two consecutive Fibonacci numbers [1 to 144].
The minimalistic visual effect is then personalized by the palettes of 15 artists who embraced the invitation to give their personal contribution to the collection. The palette name and the author name is displayed in the features along with the Fibonacci numbers ratio, the colors number vs the total palette color number, the background color, the total number of rectangles and the depth level of recursion achieved by the algorithm.
Immerse yourself in this generative project, inspired by geometrism and abstract expressionism. 
Lose yourself in the beauty of a digital garden.

metadata.name: PolyGem #122
metadata.description:
PolyGem is inspired by my own experience when I was a child. I liked play with sands, rocks and many different beautiful stones. They had different layers with colorful textures and crystal structures. All of them caught my curiosity and my time after school.

In this project, I try to remember and describe my experience about beautiful stones and gems with abstract arts. Four types of layouts are designed and each with a recursive algorithm to construct the crystal structures. Five textures are picked to mimic the complex patterns inside of crystal cells. All above them are combining in a random way, but are balanced with local structures.

Variables:
- 4 layouts
- 5 textures
- 20 color sets

Please be patient with drawing process.

metadata.name: Tempus Fugit #9
metadata.description:
As we're growing up, time is just a number we often don't even notice. 
We notice its passing but rarely consider the importance of its true value.

Tick.Tock.Tick.Tock.

As we get older, we tend to see time from a different angle and, yet again, we miss what it really means... Our focus is on other things. Other "more important" things, such as money, but only a few of us understand that everything in life doesn't have a price, but rather a cost.

And while we can always earn more and more money, time is something we can't buy nor earn more of. That's the problem with time; we can never get it back. There's not enough money in this world that could give us more time.

This work is focusing on that fact. Do we still have time? With all that is happening in the world right now, climate change, pollution, and the recent possibility of nuclear war, our "dark and gloomy" art is a reminder of what could happen to all of us...

Tick.Tock.Tick.Tock

Options:
- press a, s, d, f to save hi-res PNG images

Made with p5.js, November 2022
